#1 Rectal cancer
Mr. Juarez has brought his outside pathology for review, and we will have that read here by Bay Shore Sanitarium.  He will go ahead and proceed with rectal endoscopic ultrasound to help with staging of his rectal cancer.  Although it seems that the left hepatic lobe lesion seen from outside was largely described as benign, we will go ahead and have both the CT as well as MRI over-read here by Texas Elks Care Center.  Should both of those over-read be equivocal, we may even consider an abdominal ultrasound, but I am hopeful that both MRI and CT will be sufficient.  We will arrange for him to meet with our colorectal surgeons, and should there be any evidence for invasive disease based on our evaluation, we will also make arrangements for him with our colleagues in Radiation Oncology for neoadjuvant therapy.
#2 PAME
Given Mr. Juarez's clinical history as well as functional status, he is able to proceed to any anticipated surgery regarding his rectal cancer without further evaluation.  A baseline chest radiograph, laboratory studies as well as EKG will be obtained for baseline purposes.
PATIENT EDUCATION
Ready to learn, no apparent learning barriers were identified; learning preferences include listening.  Explained diagnosis and treatment plan; patient expressed understanding of the content.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: No, not interested in additional information.

